The {{Nihongo|'''Kankoh-maru'''|観光丸|Kankōmaru|}} is the name of a proposed [[VTVL|vertical takeoff and landing]] (VTVL), [[single-stage-to-orbit]] (SSTO), [[reusable launch system]] ([[rocket]]-powered [[spacecraft]]).<ref name=sf20120804> {{cite web |last=Anderson|first=Erik |title=Kankoh-maru Flight Manual |url=http://www.spacefuture.com/archive/kankoh_maru_flight_manual.shtml |publisher=Space Future |date=July 1997 |accessdate=2012-08-04}}</ref>
==Overview== The concept was created by the {{Interlanguage link multi|Japanese Rocket Society|ja|3=日本ロケット協会|vertical-align=sup}} in 1993.<ref name="uchumaru_kankoh"> {{Cite web|url=http://www.uchumaru.com/spaceship/kankohmaru.htm|script-title=ja:準軌道宇宙旅行 宇宙丸 - 観光丸 |publisher=uchumaru.com |language=Japanese |trans-title=Suborbital space tourism Uchumaru - Kankoh-maru |date=2005-04-11 |accessdate=2011-07-24}}</ref>{{request quotation|date=August 2012}}<!-- need a quotation, in English, to verify the claim; none of this claim is supported in the main English language source (Anderson, 1997) --> This development cost was estimated [[Japanese yen|¥]]2.67 trillion ([[United States dollar|$]]28 billion) in 1995.<ref name="uchumaru_kankoh" />{{request quotation|date=August 2012}}<!-- need a quotation, in English, to verify the claim; none of this claim is supported in the main English language source (Anderson, 1997) -->
The name ''[[Kankō Maru]]'' is derived from the [[Japanese barque Kankō Maru|first steam-powered vessel in Edo-era Japan]].<ref name="uchumaru_kankoh" />
